You’re right. I conflated two models.

Better design: each request has **one requesting principal**, normalized from exactly one issuer:

```ts
policy.evaluate({
  principal,      // either GitHub Actions OR GCP service account
  tokenRequest,   // normalized GitHub App slug, resource, permissions
})
```

Where `principal` is a discriminated union:

```ts
type IssuancePrincipal =
  | { kind: "github_actions"; repository; workflowRef; ref; eventName; ... }
  | { kind: "gcp_service_account"; email; projectId; subject; ... };
```

Then a single combined policy is reasonable:

```json
{
  "id": "deploy-service-may-write-target-repo",
  "principal": {
    "kind": "gcp_service_account",
    "email": "deploy-service@project.iam.gserviceaccount.com"
  },
  "tokenRequest": {
    "githubAppSlug": "example-app",
    "resource": "https://api.github.com/repos/chikachow/example",
    "permissions": {
      "contents": "write"
    }
  }
}
```

And GitHub Actions rules remain the same shape, just under `principal.kind = "github_actions"`.

This keeps it manageable because the shared rule shape is:

- who is asking: issuer-specific principal matcher
- what token they want: shared GitHub App token request matcher

For GCP callers, Cloud Run IAM should still be the coarse outer gate, but the application should verify the Google OIDC token when it is the request principal, so it can apply exact per-service-account policy and log deny reasons consistently.

So the corrected plan is: **one issuer-aware issuance policy, one principal per request, shared token request authorization, with issuer-specific principal parsing/matching.**

